T1  - Testing the random walk hypothesis on Swedish stock prices: 1919–1990
AU  - Frennberg, Per
AU  - Hansson, Björn
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 17
IS  - 1
SP  - 175
EP  - 191
PY  - 1993
DA  - 1993/02/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0378-4266(93)90087-T
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/037842669390087T
AB  - This paper tests the random walk hypothesis on a new set of monthly data for the Swedish stock market, 1919–1990. We use both the variance ratio test and the test of autoregressions of multiperiod returns. Our results suggest that Swedish stock prices have not followed a random walk in the past 72 years. For short investment horizons, one to twelve months, we find strong evidence of positively autocorrelated returns. For longer horizons, two years or more, we find indications of negative autocorrelation, so called ‘mean reversion’. Our results are in line with recent research on the U.S. stock market and may have several implications for the practical investor. They point in particular towards a larger proportion of stocks in the portfolio for long term investors.
ER  - 

