T1  - Bank capital regulation and the valuation effects of Latin American debt moratoriums
AU  - Slovin, Myron B.
AU  - Jayanti, Subbarao V.
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 17
IS  - 1
SP  - 159
EP  - 174
PY  - 1993
DA  - 1993/02/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0378-4266(93)90086-S
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/037842669390086S
AB  - We examine effects of the Mexican and Bolivian debt moratoriums on bank share prices and analyze whether bank capital regulation influences these returns. We hypothesize that investors perceived that capital deficient banks with exposure to this debt would sustain greater regulatory costs due to increased pressure from regulators to strengthen their capital bases or to reduce leverage. Consistent with this hypothesis, we find that the impact of these debt moratoriums on bank stock returns is more unfavorable for capital deficient banks than for banks that met regulatory standards of capital adequacy.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - International stock market linkages: Evidence from the pre- and post-October 1987 period
AU  - Arshanapalli, Bala
AU  - Doukas, John
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 17
IS  - 1
SP  - 193
EP  - 208
PY  - 1993
DA  - 1993/02/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0378-4266(93)90088-U
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/037842669390088U
AB  - This paper uses recent developments in the theory of cointegration to provide new methods of testing the linkage and dynamic interactions among stock market movements. Our findings are in sharp contrast with previous research which discovered strong interdependence among national stock markets prior to October 1987. For the post-October 1987 period, however, our results show that the degree of international co-movements among stock price indices has increased substantially, with the Nikkei index the only exception. Furthermore, the US stock market is found to have a considerable impact on the French, German and UK markets in the post-crash period. We also find the response of the French, German and UK markets to US stock market innovations to be consistent with the view of cross-border informationally efficient stock markets. Finally, we find the Japanese equity market performance to have no links with both the US stock market and the stock markets in France, Germany and UK during the pre-and post-October crash period.
ER  - 

